; contingency-dsl v1.x — Core-Stateful Grammar
;
; Additive grammar extension for the Core-Stateful layer.
; Core-Stateful schedules have criteria computed from runtime state
; (response history, trial outcomes, elapsed time as continuous function),
; as opposed to Core schedules whose criteria are literal values.
;
; All parameters are declarative (determined at parse time).
; Evaluation of criteria is delegated to the runtime (contingency-core).
;
; This file defines production rules to be appended to schema/core/grammar.ebnf.
; No existing Core production rules are modified.
;
; Integration point (additive to Core grammar):
;   modifier ::= dr_mod | pr_mod | repeat | lag_mod | pctl_mod
;
; Reference: RFC_CORE_STATEFUL_2026-04-13.md
;            .local/percentile/RFC.md

; =====================================================================
; §1. Percentile Schedule — Platt (1973); Galbicka (1994)
; =====================================================================
;
; A differential reinforcement procedure in which the criterion is
; dynamically computed from the subject's recent response distribution.
; Only responses meeting a specified percentile of the distribution
; on a given response dimension are reinforced.
;
; Syntax:
;   Pctl(IRT, 50)                            -- minimal
;   Pctl(IRT, 25, window=30)                 -- with explicit window
;   Pctl(latency, 75, window=50, dir=above)  -- fully specified
;
; Positional arguments:
;   1. pctl_target (required): response dimension to measure
;   2. pctl_rank   (required): percentile threshold (integer 0–100)
;
; Keyword arguments:
;   window (optional): positive integer, default 20
;   dir    (optional): "below" | "above", default "below"
;
; LL(2) disambiguation:
;   After "Pctl" token, expect "(". Inside parentheses:
;   - First argument: pctl_target (one of the enumerated identifiers)
;   - After comma: pctl_rank (number)
;   - After comma: peek — if IDENT followed by "=", parse as pctl_kw_arg
;
; Platt, J. R. (1973). Percentile reinforcement: Paradigms for experimental
;   analysis of response shaping. In G. H. Bower (Ed.), The psychology of
;   learning and motivation (Vol. 7, pp. 271-296). Academic Press.
;
; Galbicka, G. (1994). Shaping in the 21st century: Moving percentile
;   schedules into applied settings. Journal of Applied Behavior Analysis,
;   27(4), 739-760. https://doi.org/10.1901/jaba.1994.27-739

pctl_mod        ::= "Pctl" "(" pctl_target "," pctl_rank ("," pctl_kw_arg)* ")"

pctl_target     ::= "IRT"
                  | "latency"
                  | "duration"
                  | "force"
                  | "rate"

pctl_rank       ::= number                          -- integer 0–100 (semantic constraint P1)

pctl_kw_arg     ::= "window" "=" number              -- positive integer (semantic constraint P2)
                  | "dir" "=" pctl_dir

pctl_dir        ::= "below" | "above"

; === Reserved words (additive to grammar.ebnf `reserved`) ===

; reserved      ::= ... (existing)
;                 | "Pctl"
;                 | pctl_target                       -- IRT, latency, duration, force, rate
;                 | "window" | "dir"
;                 | pctl_dir                          -- below, above
;
; Note: pctl_target values other than "IRT" begin with lowercase letters.
; They appear only inside Pctl(...) parentheses, so parser context
; disambiguates from let-binding identifiers. A let-binding named
; "latency" at top level does NOT collide because pctl_target is
; parsed only after the "Pctl" "(" token sequence.

; === Semantic constraints ===
;
; P1. pctl_rank must be an integer in [0, 100].
;     Non-integer or out-of-range → SemanticError (PCTL_INVALID_RANK).
;
; P2. pctl_window (if specified) must be a positive integer (≥ 1).
;     Zero, negative, or non-integer → SemanticError (PCTL_INVALID_WINDOW).
;     Omission → default value 20.
;
; P3. pctl_target must be one of the enumerated values.
;     Unknown target → SemanticError (PCTL_UNKNOWN_TARGET).
;
; P4. pctl_dir (if specified) must be "below" or "above".
;     Unknown dir → SemanticError (PCTL_INVALID_DIR).
;     Omission → default value "below".
;
; P5. pctl_rank must NOT carry a time unit.
;     `Pctl(IRT, 50s)` → SemanticError (PCTL_UNEXPECTED_TIME_UNIT).
;     Rationale: rank is a dimensionless percentile, not a temporal quantity.
;
; P6. Duplicate keyword arguments → SemanticError (DUPLICATE_PCTL_KW_ARG).
;     E.g., `Pctl(IRT, 50, window=20, window=30)` → error.
;
; W1. pctl_rank == 0 or 100 → Linter WARNING (PCTL_EXTREME_RANK).
;     Rationale: rank=0 reinforces all responses (CRF equivalent),
;     rank=100 reinforces no responses (EXT equivalent).
;
; W2. pctl_window < 5 → Linter WARNING (PCTL_SMALL_WINDOW).
;     Rationale: distribution stability. Platt (1973) recommended window ≥ 20.
;
; W3. pctl_window > 100 → Linter WARNING (PCTL_LARGE_WINDOW).
;     Rationale: adaptiveness degrades. Research typically uses 10–50.

; =====================================================================
; §2. Adjusting Schedule — Blough (1958); Ferster & Skinner (1957);
;                          Mazur (1987); Richards et al. (1997)
; =====================================================================
;
; A procedural framework in which a schedule parameter (delay, ratio,
; or amount) is systematically adjusted based on the subject's recent
; performance. The adjustment converges toward the subject's behavioral
; equilibrium (indifference point) or threshold.
;
; Unlike Pctl (a modifier that changes reinforcement criteria), Adj is
; a standalone schedule expression that defines a contingency whose
; parameter value changes across trials.
;
; Syntax:
;   Adj(delay, start=10s, step=1s)                     -- minimal
;   Adj(delay, start=10s, step=2s, min=0s, max=120s)   -- with bounds
;   Adj(ratio, start=5, step=2)                        -- adjusting-ratio
;   Adj(ratio, start=5, step=2, min=1, max=100)        -- with bounds
;   Adj(amount, start=3, step=1, min=1, max=10)        -- adjusting-amount
;   Adjusting(delay, start=10s, step=1s)               -- verbose alias
;
; Positional arguments:
;   1. adj_target (required): what parameter is adjusted
;
; Keyword arguments:
;   start (required): initial parameter value
;   step  (required): adjustment magnitude per step (additive)
;   min   (optional): lower bound on adjusted parameter
;   max   (optional): upper bound on adjusted parameter
;
; LL(2) disambiguation:
;   After "Adj" / "Adjusting" token, expect "(". Inside parentheses:
;   - First argument: adj_target (one of the enumerated identifiers)
;   - After comma: peek — IDENT followed by "=" → parse as adj_kw_arg
;
; Integration point (additive to Core grammar):
;   base_schedule ::= ... | adj_schedule
;
; Note: Adj extends base_schedule (not modifier), because it defines a
; standalone contingency structure, not a criterion modification.
; This differs from Pctl which extends modifier.
;
; Ferster, C. B., & Skinner, B. F. (1957). Schedules of reinforcement.
;   Appleton-Century-Crofts.
; Blough, D. S. (1958). A method for obtaining psychophysical thresholds
;   from the pigeon. JEAB, 1(1), 31-43.
;   https://doi.org/10.1901/jeab.1958.1-31
; Mazur, J. E. (1987). An adjusting procedure for studying delayed
;   reinforcement. In M. L. Commons et al. (Eds.), Quantitative analyses
;   of behavior (Vol. 5, pp. 55-73). Erlbaum.
; Richards, J. B., Mitchell, S. H., de Wit, H., & Seiden, L. S. (1997).
;   Determination of discount functions in rats with an adjusting-amount
;   procedure. JEAB, 67(3), 353-366.
;   https://doi.org/10.1901/jeab.1997.67-353

adj_schedule    ::= ("Adj" | "Adjusting") "(" adj_target ("," adj_kw_arg)+ ")"

adj_target      ::= "delay"
                  | "ratio"
                  | "amount"

adj_kw_arg      ::= "start" "=" value
                  | "step"  "=" value
                  | "min"   "=" value
                  | "max"   "=" value

; === Reserved words (additive to grammar.ebnf `reserved`) ===

; reserved      ::= ... (existing)
;                 | "Adj" | "Adjusting"
;                 | adj_target                       -- delay, ratio, amount
;                 | "step" | "min" | "max"           -- adj keyword argument names
;
; Note: "start" is already reserved by PR (pr_param). Reused here with
; compatible semantics (initial parameter value).
;
; adj_target values (delay, ratio, amount) begin with lowercase letters.
; They appear only inside Adj(...) / Adjusting(...) parentheses, so
; parser context disambiguates from let-binding identifiers. A let-binding
; named "delay" at top level does NOT collide because adj_target is parsed
; only after the "Adj" "(" or "Adjusting" "(" token sequence.

; === Semantic constraints ===
;
; A1. adj_start (start keyword) is required. Omission → SemanticError
;     (MISSING_ADJ_PARAM).
;
; A2. adj_step (step keyword) is required. Omission → SemanticError
;     (MISSING_ADJ_PARAM).
;
; A3. adj_target must be one of the enumerated values.
;     Unknown target → SemanticError (ADJ_UNKNOWN_TARGET).
;
; A4. adj_start must be positive (> 0).
;     Zero or negative → SemanticError (ADJ_NONPOSITIVE_START).
;     Rationale: zero delay is CRF, zero ratio is undefined, zero amount
;     is no reinforcement. None are meaningful starting points.
;
; A5. adj_step must be positive (> 0).
;     Zero or negative → SemanticError (ADJ_NONPOSITIVE_STEP).
;     Rationale: step=0 means no adjustment ever occurs — use a fixed
;     schedule instead. Negative step is meaningless (direction is
;     determined by runtime, not by sign).
;
; A6. For "delay" target: start, step, min, max MUST include a time unit
;     (s/ms/min). Dimensionless → SemanticError (ADJ_TIME_UNIT_REQUIRED).
;     Rationale: delay is intrinsically temporal (Mazur, 1987).
;
; A7. For "ratio" target: start, step, min, max must NOT include a time
;     unit. Time unit → SemanticError (ADJ_UNEXPECTED_TIME_UNIT).
;     Rationale: ratio counts responses, not time.
;
; A8. For "amount" target: start, step, min, max must NOT include a time
;     unit. Time unit → SemanticError (ADJ_UNEXPECTED_TIME_UNIT).
;     Rationale: amount is dimensionless in DSL; units are runtime-interpreted.
;
; A9. min < max (when both specified).
;     min >= max → SemanticError (ADJ_INVALID_BOUNDS).
;
; A10. start must be in [min, max] (when bounds specified).
;      start < min or start > max → SemanticError (ADJ_START_OUT_OF_BOUNDS).
;
; A11. For "ratio" target: start, step, min, max must be integers.
;      Non-integer → SemanticError (ADJ_RATIO_NOT_INTEGER).
;      Rationale: FR values are integers (response counts).
;
; A12. Duplicate keyword arguments → SemanticError (DUPLICATE_ADJ_KW_ARG).
;      E.g., `Adj(delay, start=10s, start=20s)` → error.
;
; W1. "delay" target without max specified → Linter WARNING
;     (ADJ_UNBOUNDED_DELAY). Rationale: unbounded delay growth may exceed
;     session duration. Safety concern.
;
; W2. step > start → Linter WARNING (ADJ_LARGE_STEP).
;     Rationale: the first downward adjustment would produce a value ≤ 0
;     (if min is not specified or min=0).
;
; W3. min=0 with "delay" target → Linter WARNING (ADJ_ZERO_MIN_DELAY).
;     Rationale: delay=0 is immediate reinforcement (CRF equivalent).
;     Typically intentional in some paradigms but worth flagging.
;
; W4. "ratio" target with min < 1 → Linter WARNING (ADJ_SUBUNIT_RATIO).
;     Rationale: FR < 1 is procedurally undefined (fewer than one response
;     for reinforcement).

; =====================================================================
; §3. Interlocking Schedule — Ferster & Skinner (1957)
; =====================================================================
;
; A compound schedule in which ratio and interval requirements interlock:
; the ratio requirement decreases linearly as time elapses since the last
; reinforcement. At each reinforcement, the ratio resets to its initial
; value (R0).
;
; Mathematical formulation:
;   R(t) = max(1, ⌈R0 × (1 − t/T)⌉)
;
; Where:
;   R0 = initial ratio requirement (immediately post-reinforcement)
;   T  = time window (when elapsed time = T, ratio = 1 = CRF)
;   t  = elapsed time since last reinforcement
;
; Syntax:
;   Interlock(R0=250, T=5min)          -- standard form
;   Interlocking(R0=250, T=5min)       -- verbose alias
;   Interlock(R0=300, T=10min)         -- F&S 1957 original example
;   Interlock(R0=16, T=80s)            -- Powers (1968) condition
;
; Keyword arguments:
;   R0 (required): initial ratio requirement (positive integer, dimensionless)
;   T  (required): time window / decay period (positive, time unit required)
;
; Both parameters are required; there are no defaults.
;
; LL(2) disambiguation:
;   After "Interlock" / "Interlocking" token, expect "(". Inside:
;   "R0" "=" or "T" "=" identifies keyword arguments.
;
; Integration point (additive to Core grammar):
;   base_schedule ::= ... | interlock_schedule
;
; Note on "T" as keyword name:
;   grammar.ebnf defines domain ::= "T" (for time-based schedules FT/VT/RT).
;   As an interlock_kw_arg, "T" appears only inside Interlock(...) parentheses
;   in the context IDENT "=" value. The parser's position (inside Interlock
;   parens, expecting keyword args) disambiguates from the domain production
;   (which follows dist in atomic_or_second). No syntactic ambiguity.
;
; Note on "R0" as keyword name:
;   R0 is the first alphanumeric (letter + digit) keyword in the DSL.
;   This follows the mathematical convention for the initial ratio parameter
;   (R₀) in the F&S 1957 formulation. The digit is intentional to match the
;   subscript notation used universally in the literature.
;
; Naming collision resolution:
;   "Interlocking" in the DSL refers to Ferster & Skinner (1957) schedules.
;   Glenn (2004) "Interlocking Behavioral Contingencies" (metacontingency)
;   uses the annotation @ibc (renamed from @interlocking to resolve the
;   collision). See INTERLOCK_SCHEDULE_DESIGN_2026-04-13.md §6.
;
; Ferster, C. B., & Skinner, B. F. (1957). Schedules of reinforcement.
;   Appleton-Century-Crofts.
; Berryman, R., & Nevin, J. A. (1962). Interlocking schedules of
;   reinforcement. JEAB, 5(2), 213-223.
;   https://doi.org/10.1901/jeab.1962.5-213
; Powers, R. B. (1968). Clock-delivered reinforcers in conjunctive and
;   interlocking schedules. JEAB, 11(5), 579-586.
;   https://doi.org/10.1901/jeab.1968.11-579

interlock_schedule ::= ("Interlock" | "Interlocking") "(" interlock_kw_arg ("," interlock_kw_arg)* ")"

interlock_kw_arg   ::= "R0" "=" value
                     | "T"  "=" value

; === Reserved words (additive to grammar.ebnf `reserved`) ===

; reserved      ::= ... (existing)
;                 | "Interlock" | "Interlocking"
;                 | "R0"                          -- initial ratio (F&S mathematical notation)
;
; Note: "T" is already used as domain ::= "T" in Core grammar.
; As interlock_kw_arg, it is context-dependent reserved (parsed only
; inside Interlock/Interlocking parentheses). No collision.

; === Semantic constraints ===
;
; I1. R0 is required. Omission → SemanticError (MISSING_INTERLOCK_PARAM).
;
; I2. T is required. Omission → SemanticError (MISSING_INTERLOCK_PARAM).
;
; I3. R0 must be a positive integer (> 0).
;     Zero, negative, or non-integer → SemanticError (INTERLOCK_INVALID_R0).
;     Rationale: R0 counts responses; R0=0 means no reinforcement condition.
;
; I4. R0 must NOT carry a time unit.
;     `Interlock(R0=250s, T=5min)` → SemanticError
;     (INTERLOCK_UNEXPECTED_TIME_UNIT).
;     Rationale: R0 is a dimensionless response count.
;
; I5. T must be positive (> 0).
;     Zero or negative → SemanticError (INTERLOCK_NONPOSITIVE_T).
;     Rationale: T=0 makes R(t) undefined (division by zero in the formula).
;
; I6. T must include a time unit (s/ms/min).
;     Dimensionless → SemanticError (INTERLOCK_TIME_UNIT_REQUIRED).
;     Rationale: time window is intrinsically temporal.
;
; I7. Duplicate keyword arguments → SemanticError
;     (DUPLICATE_INTERLOCK_KW_ARG).
;     E.g., `Interlock(R0=100, R0=200, T=5min)` → error.
;
; W1. R0 == 1 → Linter WARNING (INTERLOCK_TRIVIAL_RATIO).
;     Rationale: R0=1 means the ratio requirement starts at 1 and can only
;     remain 1 (max(1, 1×(1-t/T)) = 1 for all t). Effectively FT(T).
;     Use FT if this is the intent.
;
; W2. R0 > 500 → Linter WARNING (INTERLOCK_LARGE_RATIO).
;     Rationale: very high initial ratio may produce ratio strain.
;     F&S 1957 used R0=300. Research typically uses R0 ≤ 300.
